<paragraph blockId="2.[136,1452,1718,2069]" lastBlockId="3.[136,1451,158,221]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="232" pageId="2" pageNumber="231">
Thallus corticolous, distinctly corticate, light brownish to greenish grey, smooth to uneven. 
<emphasis box="[1243,1353,1935,1961]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="231">Ascomata</emphasis>
solitary, with apical, separate ostioles, 
<quantity box="[488,607,1971,1997]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="231" unit="mm" value="1.15" valueMax="1.3" valueMin="1.0">1–1.3 mm</quantity>
diam, immersed-erumpent, covered by thallus except for the protruding ostiolar area, the latter with yellow pigment pruina, darkening when dry. 
<emphasis box="[971,1128,2006,2032]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="231">Hamathecium</emphasis>
inspersed. 
<emphasis box="[1258,1385,2007,2033]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="231">Ascospores</emphasis>
4 per ascus, muriform, with 9–11 primary transverse septa (the median cells further divided by secondary transverse septa) and 1–3 longitudinal septa, with the distinct diamond-shaped lumina and with a slight constriction at the median septum, narrowly ellipsoid to fusiform, 100–120 × 27–30 µm, IKI+ blue.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5425880" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5425880" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5425880/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="232" startId="3.[136,234,1219,1241]" targetBox="[172,1417,252,1186]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1453,1219,1277]" pageId="3" pageNumber="232">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,258,1219,1241]" pageId="3" pageNumber="232">FIGURE 2.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="A. Thallus" authorityName="A. Thallus" box="[264,596,1219,1241]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Trypetheliaceae" genus="Astrothelium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Trypetheliales" pageId="3" pageNumber="232" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="rogitamae">
<emphasis box="[264,491,1219,1241]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="232">Astrothelium rogitamae</emphasis>
A. Thallus
</taxonomicName>
with perithecia; B. Perithecium enlarged showing pigmented ostiolar area. C. Ascospore. D. Ascospore showing IKI + blue reaction. Scale = 1 mm in A–B, 10 µm in C–D.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,1323,1782]" pageId="3" pageNumber="232">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,315,1323,1349]" pageId="3" pageNumber="232">Chemistry</emphasis>
: Secondary substances absent except for a yellow pigment around the ostiole; thallus surface UV-, K-, ostiolar pigment 
<collectionCode box="[326,347,1360,1386]" country="United Kingdom" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15867" name="Royal Botanic Gardens" pageId="3" pageNumber="232" type="Herbarium">K</collectionCode>
+ blood-red, UV-.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,1323,1782]" pageId="3" pageNumber="232">
This is a second new species with amyloid ascospores, differing from the preceding one mainly in the yellowpigmented, protruding ostiolar area and in the formation of secondary transverse septa in the median cells. Only one other species of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Aptroot &amp; Lucking" baseAuthorityYear="2016" box="[324,468,1467,1493]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Trypetheliaceae" genus="Astrothelium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Trypetheliales" pageId="3" pageNumber="232" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[324,468,1467,1493]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="232">Astrothelium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known with a combination of pigments and amyloid, muriform ascospores, namely 
<taxonomicName box="[136,299,1503,1530]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Trypetheliaceae" genus="Astrothelium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Trypetheliales" pageId="3" pageNumber="232" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="flavoduplex">
<emphasis box="[136,299,1503,1530]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="232">A. flavoduplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It deviates by producing lichexanthone (
<collectionCode box="[769,811,1504,1530]" country="Colombia" name="Departamento de Biologia de la Universidad del Valle" pageId="3" pageNumber="232">UV</collectionCode>
+ yellow) and by the strongly pseudostromatic ascomata covered with with yellow-orange pigment, as well as the longer ascospores (110–350 × 20–27 µm). 
<collectionCode box="[1242,1261,1540,1566]" country="USA" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15406" name="Harvard University - Arnold Arboretum" pageId="3" pageNumber="232" type="Herbarium">A</collectionCode>
morphologically similar species but with I-negative ascospores is 
<taxonomicName authority="(Makhija &amp; Patw.) Aptroot &amp; Lucking" authorityName="Aptroot &amp; Lucking" baseAuthorityName="Makhija &amp; Patw." box="[695,1250,1575,1602]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Trypetheliaceae" genus="Astrothelium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Trypetheliales" pageId="3" pageNumber="232" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="vezdai">
<emphasis box="[695,800,1575,1602]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="232">A. vezdai</emphasis>
(Makhija &amp; Patw.) Aptroot &amp; Lücking
</taxonomicName>
, which has larger and much broader ascospores (80–175 × 25–50 µm) and the ostiolar pigment is orange rather than yellow (
<bibRefCitation author="Aptroot, A. &amp; Lucking, R." pageId="3" pageNumber="232" pagination="763 - 982" refId="ref2588" refString="Aptroot, A. &amp; Lucking, R. (2016) A revisionary synopsis of the Trypetheliaceae (Ascomycota: Trypetheliales). Lichenologist 48: 763 - 982. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0024282916000487" type="journal article" year="2016">Aptroot &amp; Lücking 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
